<p><a href="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/oysterscrepinette.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-6471" src="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/oysterscrepinette-710x536.jpg" alt="oysterscrepinette" width="710" height="536" srcset="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/oysterscrepinette-710x536.jpg 710w, http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/oysterscrepinette-300x226.jpg 300w, http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/oysterscrepinette-768x580.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 710px) 100vw, 710px" /></a></p>
<p><strong>Cr√©pinettes</strong> are little sausage parcels wrapped in caul fat that people in our Bordelais region traditionally have for Christmas. They are always served with oysters and they make a perfect pair. I guess it&#8217;s the French version of <em>&#8220;surf &amp; turf</em>&#8220;. Haha!</p>
<p><a href="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/guinefowl.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-6472" src="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/guinefowl-710x1064.jpg" alt="guinefowl" width="710" height="1064" srcset="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/guinefowl-710x1064.jpg 710w, http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/guinefowl-200x300.jpg 200w, http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/guinefowl-768x1151.jpg 768w, http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/guinefowl.jpg 1513w" sizes="(max-width: 710px) 100vw, 710px" /></a></p>
<p><strong>Roast guinea fowl with chestnuts, apples and red cabbage</strong></p>
<p>1 large guinea fowl, approx. 3 to 4 pounds/ 1.5-1.8 kg (you can alternate and use a chicken instead)<br />
1 medium-sized red cabbage<br />
3 red onions, peeled and quartered<br />
20 ounces/ 570 g peeled cooked chestnuts<br />
8 small red apples, quartered<br />
A glass or two of Bordeaux red wine (or any of your favourite cooking wine)<br />
¬º cup/ 60 g unsalted butter, in small chunks<br />
Olive oil<br />
A small bunch of thyme, rosemary and a bay leaf<br />
Salt and pepper</p>
<p>Preheat the oven to 350¬∞F/180¬∞C.</p>
<p>Season the guinea fowl inside and out with salt and pepper.</p>
<p>Slice the cabbage into 1 inch/2.5 cm large strips. Slice the onions and apples into quarters, (leaving stems on).</p>
<p>In a medium-sized pan, heat olive oil and saut√© one of the onions for 3 minutes. Season with salt and pepper. Then add a handful of chestnuts and a handful of cabbage. You just want enough to insert into the bird‚Äôs cavity for the stuffing.</p>
<p>Drizzle the roasting pan with olive oil. Stuff the bird with the saut√©ed vegetables and the thyme, rosemary and bay leaf.</p>
<p>Place bird in the center of the pan and scatter the apples, onions, cabbage and chestnuts. Season with salt and pepper, and drizzle the bird and vegetables with olive oil.</p>
<p>Transfer pan to the preheated oven and cook for 1 hour and 20 minutes. After 1 hour drizzle the pan with red wine and scatter small chunks of butter all over the vegetables.</p>
<p>Leave the bird to rest before carving and toss all the veggies together so they get coated with the sauce.</p>
<p><a href="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/chestnutcake.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-6473" src="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/chestnutcake-710x1059.jpg" alt="chestnutcake" width="710" height="1059" srcset="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/chestnutcake-710x1059.jpg 710w, http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/chestnutcake-201x300.jpg 201w, http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/chestnutcake-768x1145.jpg 768w, http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/chestnutcake.jpg 1521w" sizes="(max-width: 710px) 100vw, 710px" /></a></p>
<p><strong>Vanilla Chestnut cake</strong></p>
<p>18 ounces/ 500 g cr√®me de marron (sweetened vanilla chestnut cream)<br />
1/2 cup/55 g self-raising flour, sifted<br />
4 eggs, separated<br />
1/3 cup/80 g salted-butter + extra for the pan, softened at room temperature<br />
4 Glazed chestnuts/ marrons glac√©s (optional)<br />
Confectioner‚Äôs sugar, for dusting</p>
<p>Preheat the oven to 350¬∞F/180¬∞C.</p>
<p>In a large bowl, whisk the egg yolks, softened salted-butter and chestnut cream until smooth. Fold in the flour. Whisk the egg whites until stiff and gently fold them into the mixture.</p>
<p>Generously butter a cake pan, approx 9 inches, or medium-sized bundt pan (like I did), and dust with a little flour. Shake off any excess flour, then pour the cake batter into the cake pan.</p>
<p>Bake for approximately 40 minutes, or until the cake is golden. (please note that a Bundt pan will take slightly longer because it is deeper).</p>
<p>You can decorate with glazed chestnuts (optional) for a more festive touch. Sprinkle with confectioner‚Äôs sugar.</p>
<p><a href="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/chestnutcake2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-6474" src="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/chestnutcake2-203x300.jpg" alt="chestnutcake2" width="203" height="300" srcset="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/chestnutcake2-203x300.jpg 203w, http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/chestnutcake2-768x1134.jpg 768w, http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/chestnutcake2-710x1048.jpg 710w, http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/chestnutcake2.jpg 1536w" sizes="(max-width: 203px) 100vw, 203px" /></a></p>

