          <h3 class="entry-title"><a href="http://mimithorisson.com/2016/10/25/our-big-day-the-book-is-out/" rel="bookmark">OUR BIG DAY &#8211; THE BOOK IS OUT!</a></h3>
          <!-- <h4 class="vcard author">by <span class="fn">mimithorisson</span></h4> -->
          
          <div class="entry-content">

              <p><a href="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/mimioranges.jpg"><img src="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/mimioranges-710x536.jpg" alt="mimioranges" width="710" height="536" class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-6430" srcset="http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/mimioranges-710x536.jpg 710w, http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/mimioranges-300x226.jpg 300w, http://4ei1we1252c14dmfxx37crrd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/mimioranges-768x580.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 710px) 100vw, 710px" /></a></p>
<p>On an evening in late January 2014 I called Rica, my editor at Clarkson Potter.  I had just (almost) finished my first cookbook &#8211; although according to Rica &#8220;we still had so much work to do&#8221;. The phone call was scheduled so we could go over the next steps, the cover, the title, all the final changes and improvements. But that night something else was on my mind. Not my first cookbook, which was published in October 2014, but my next cookbook, the one I had been obsessing about for a few days and nobody knew about except Oddur and I.</p>
<p>Rica was a little startled. &#8220;I think we need to finish this one first&#8221; she said, although she loved the idea and gave me encouragement that she&#8217;d be interested in the second book. In fact she was so supportive that she turned up when we did the pop-up, marshalled the kitchen and the dining room (that&#8217;s her holding the menu at one of the lunches &#8211; thanks Rica) There were of course a few minor details to sort out first, like buying the house that would play a key part in the second book. Then renovating it, moving into it &#8230; </p>
<p>That night I felt like a kid in early January, just after Christmas. Next Christmas seemed so very far away. So much to do before we&#8217;d ever get there. When I look back at all the steps, moments and the fair share of madness that went into making this book I&#8217;m surprised we even managed at all. But in those early days it all felt very distant. </p>
<p>We eventually managed to buy the house, renovate most of it, we did a pop-up restaurant, I wrote the book, cooked the recipes, we photographed it all. And as if by miracle the day that I felt would never come is here today. </p>
<p>Today is our big day!</p>
